atin <i>branca</i> ‘foot, paw’), of uncertain application (compare German   Zweig  ); or a habitational name from (La) Branche, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare also   Labranche  .","English: variant of   Branch  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Zweig","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Isadore, Yochanan, Akiva, Arie, Aron, Elchanan, Hyman, Moishe, Moshe, Shimon.  German Gerd, Hans, Manfred, Reinhold, Arnulf, Herta, Kurt.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>zwīg</i> ‘branch, bough, twig, graft’, German <i>Zweig</i>, applied perhaps as a nickname for a new member in a family, offspring or as an occupational name for a horticultural expert. The Jewish surname is artificial. Compare   Branch  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"wife Richard De Braunche IV married Richard de Braunche IV before 1200, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 4 sons."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1201–Male":"1201–Surnud","1213–1271":"1213–1271","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","before 1200":"enne 1200","1213":"1213","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","ABT 1201":"umbes 1201","1220":"1220","15 December 1213":"15. detsember 1213","about 1220":"umbes 1220","1271":"1271","1170":"1170","Gresham, Norfolk, , England":"Gresham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Great Melton, Norfolk, England":"Great Melton, Norfolk, England","Gresham, Norfolk Co., England":"Gresham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Frome, Somerset, England":"Frome, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1201–Male":"1201–Kuollut","1213–1271":"1213–1271","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","before 1200":"ennen vuotta 1200","1213":"1213","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","ABT 1201":"noin 1201","1220":"1220","15 December 1213":"15. joulukuuta 1213","about 1220":"noin 1220","1271":"1271","1170":"1170","Gresham, Norfolk, , England":"Gresham, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Europe":"Europe","Great Melton, Norfolk, England":"Great Melton, Norfolk, England","Gresham, Norfolk Co., England":"Gresham, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Frome, Somerset, England":"Frome, Somerset, England"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1170–Male":"1170–Décédé","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","1201–Male":"1201–Décédé","1213–1271":"1213–1271","1220–Male":"1220–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée